{ This position shows why the defending king must reach the short side (the side with fewer files between king and pawn). Here White wins by advancing the king to e7, cutting off the black king from the queening file and reaching the Lucena setup. The key is that Black's rook on the long side cannot generate enough checks to stop the king march once White's king reaches the sixth rank. Compare with the previous chapter: Black's rook is on the wrong side here, giving White a clear road to the Lucena position. }
1. Kd6+ (1. Kd7 Kf6 2. e7 Kf7 $10) (1. Ra1 Rb7+ 2. Kd8 Rb8+ 3. Kc7 Rb2 4. Rf1 Ra2 5. e7 Ra7+ $10) 1... Kf6 2. Kd7 Kg7 3. Ke7 Kg6 (3... Rb1 4. Ra8 Rb7+ 5. Kd6 Rb6+ 6. Kd7 Rb7+ 7. Kc6 Re7 8. Kd6 Rb7 9. e7) 4. Ra1 Rb7+ 5. Kd8 Rb8+ (5... Kf6 6. e7 Rb8+ 7. Kd7 Re8 8. Kd6 Rb8 9. Rf1+ Kg7 10. Kc7 Ra8 11. Ra1) 6. Kc7 Rb2 7. Re1 Rc2+ 8. Kd7 Rd2+ 9. Ke8 Ra2 10. e7 *


