{ A practical example of the lateral checking defense. Black draws cleanly with 1...Ra4! (or 1...Rb4) — cutting off the White king horizontally along the 4th rank so it cannot advance to escort the pawn. With sufficient checking distance, the rook harasses the king sideways indefinitely and White cannot make progress. The inaccuracy 1...Kg5? does not lose by force but surrenders the simplest defensive setup, leading to a more complex defense that requires precise follow-up. The lesson: when the defending king cannot reach the front of the pawn, the lateral rook cutoff is the clean and reliable solution. }
1... Kg5? (1... Ra4!) 2. Ra6 Rb4 3. Ke6 Kg6?? 4. Ke7+ Kg7 5. Ra7 Rb8 6. e6 Kg6 7. Ra1 Rb7+ 8. Kd6 Rb6+ 9. Kd7 Rb7+ 10. Kc6 Rb8 11. Kc7 Rh8 (11... Rb2 12. Re1) 12. e7 Kf7 13. Kd7 Rb8 14. Rf1+ *


