[UTCTime "09:08:38"]

{ The Philidor position, analyzed by François-André Philidor in 1777, is the fundamental drawing method for the weaker side in rook and pawn versus rook endgames. Black's drawing recipe is: keep the king in front of the pawn and place the rook on the third rank (here the sixth rank from Black's perspective) until the pawn advances, then switch to checking the opposing king from behind along the eighth rank. After 1...Rb6! 2.e6 Rb1, Black gains the necessary checking distance — White's king has no shelter from the rear checks. }
{ [%cal Bb1b6,Bb6h6] }
1... Rb6 2. e6 Rb1 *


