[UTCTime "09:10:55"]

{ Same starting position as the Philidor chapter, but here Black uses a second defensive method (known as Karstedt's defense, after Max Karstedt who published it in 1897). The defining Karstedt idea is 1...Re1! — placing the rook directly behind the pawn on the e-file, preventing its advance — combined with 2...Kf8!, keeping the king on the short side near the queening square. If the king stays close to f8, White can never force a decisive position because Black answers Ra8+ with Kg7 and then returns, denying White's king the critical e7 outpost. }
{ [%cal Bb1e1,Be1e8] }
1... Re1! 2. Ke6 Kf8! (2... Kd8?! 3. Ra8+ Kc7 4. Re8 (4. Kf6 Kd7) 4... Rh1! (4... Re2? 5. Kf7 Rh2 6. Rg8 Rh7+ 7. Rg7 Rh8 8. Ke7 Kc6 9. e6 Kc7 10. Rg1) 5. Rg8 Re1 6. Rg2 Kd8 $10) 3. Ra8+ Kg7 4. Kd6 Kf7 5. Ra7+ Ke8 6. Ke6 Kf8 7. Ra8+ Kg7 8. Re8 Ra1! *


