{ Black must place the rook on the long side (the a-file) with 1...Ra1!, from where perpetual checking distance is maintained. The losing mistake 1...Rg1? abandons the long side — White replies Ra6, driving the black king away, and then Rg8! followed by g7 creates an unstoppable pawn. This chapter reinforces the key defensive principle: in rook-and-pawn-versus-rook endings, the defending rook belongs on the long side where it has maximum checking distance and can prevent the king from finding shelter. }
1... Rg1? (1... Ra1! 2. Rb6 Ra8 $10) 2. Ra6 Kf8 3. Ra8+ Ke7 4. Rg8! Rg2 5. Kh7! Kf7 6. g6+ Ke7 7. Ra8 Rh2+ 8. Kg8 Rg2 9. g7 *


