{ A practical example of a critical king-move decision in a rook ending with mutual passed pawns. Black must choose the correct direction: 1...Kd3! wins by coordinating the king with the e-pawn and rook to escort the passer, while 1...Kxe3? is a blunder that hands White the draw — after 2.Kc2 the white king blockades the pawn and Black's rook on g3 cannot break through White's Re8 defense. The lesson is that in rook endings, king activity and pawn coordination often matter more than material; the wrong king step can turn a win into an immediate draw. }
1... Kxe3? (1... Kd3! 2. Rd5+ Kxe3 3. Kc2 Ke2!? (3... Rxg3 4. Re5 Kf4 5. Re8 (5. Rd5 Kf3 6. Re5 e3 7. Kd3 Kf2) 5... Rd3 $19) 4. Rd2+ Kf3 5. Rd7 Rf8!? (5... Rxg3 6. Re7 e3 7. Kd3 Kf2) 6. Kd1 Kf2 7. Rd2+ Kf1 $19) 2. Kc2 Rxg3 3. Re8 Rg2+ $10 *


