{ Black can hold the draw with either 1...Ra5 — putting the rook behind White's pawn mass and preparing to exchange — or 1...Rb4 keeping active rook play. The losing blunder 1...Rb1?? abandons all counterplay; White's king marches in via h5 and the connected f- and g-pawns become unstoppable after g5 fxg5 f5. This practical example demonstrates that in rook endings with multiple pawns, rook activity and proper defensive positioning must never be surrendered voluntarily. }
1... Rb1?? (1... Rb4 2. f5 Rb1! 3. Kh5 Rg1!) (1... Ra5 2. g5 (2. f5 Ra1!) 2... fxg5+ 3. fxg5 Ra6 $10 (3... Ra8 $10)) 2. Kh5 Rg1 3. g5 fxg5 4. f5! Kf8 5. f6 $18 *


