{ André Chéron's 1923 study demonstrates the winning method when the defending king is too far from the pawn to establish a blockade. White wins by marching the king to b6, displacing the defending king from the ideal blockading square, and then maneuvering the rook to d1 — driving the defending rook off the d-file with tempo. The key sequence Re1! cuts off the defending rook laterally, allowing the d-pawn to advance decisively. Compare with Chéron 1923 (II) where the defending king is close enough to the pawn to hold a draw. }
1. Kc4 Rc8+ 2. Kb5 Rd8 3. Kc5 Rc8+ 4. Kb6! Rd8 5. Rd1! Kf6 6. Kc7 Rd5 7. Kc6 Ra5 (7... Rd8 8. d5 $18) 8. Re1! Ra6+ 9. Kb5 Rd6 10. Kc5 Rd8 11. d5 $18 *


