{ Chéron's 1926 study establishes a crucial exception: even with the defending king cut off far from the pawn, the position can be drawn if the king has enough maneuvering room along the edge. Here Black's king shuffles between h4, h5, and h6 while the rook maintains lateral checking distance, and White cannot break the cycle — advancing the king triggers rook checks that restore the position. White's best attempt 1.Rg2! is met by 1...Kh4!, and after 2.Rg7 Kh5 3.Rg1! the position repeats. Note: the original annotator cautions that this "no-win" pattern also applies to knight pawns (b/g-file), where two-file king cutoff is likewise insufficient. }
1. Rg2! (1. Kd4 Rd8+ 2. Kc5 Re8 3. Kd5 Rd8+ 4. Kc6 Re8 5. Re1 Kg6 6. Kd7 Ra8 (6... Re5 7. Kd6 Ra5)) 1... Kh4! 2. Rg7 (2. e5 Rxe5+ 3. Kf4 Kh3) 2... Kh5 3. Rg1! Kh6 (3... Kh4 4. e5) (3... Ra8 4. e5 Ra4 5. e6 Kh6 (5... Ra6 6. Kf4 Rxe6 7. Kf5) 6. e7 Ra8 7. Kf4 Re8 8. Kf5 Rxe7 9. Kf6) 4. Kd4 Rd8+ 5. Kc5 Re8 6. Kd5 Rd8+ 7. Ke6! Re8+ 8. Kf6! { It is important to remember that in case of a knight pawn, cuttinf off the king by two files is not sufficient to win } *


