{ Chéron's companion study to the (I) position: here the defending king is close enough to the b-pawn to maintain a draw, in contrast to the (I) study where the king was too far away. The key defensive idea is 1...Ke5!, centralizing the king and preparing to meet Rd7 with Ke6!, keeping the king on the short side. If the defending king manages to stay on e5–e6, White can never maneuver to a winning formation because the king blocks the critical path. Compared to Chéron 1923 (I): the key difference is not the file count but the defending king's ability to reach an active central square in time. }
1. Rd4 (1. Ka4 Ra8+ 2. Kb5 Rb8+ 3. Ka5 Ra8+ 4. Kb6 Rb8+ 5. Kc5) 1... Ke5! 2. Kc3 (2. Rd7 Ke6! 3. Ra7 Kd6 4. Ka4 Kc6 $10) 2... Rh8 (2... Rc8+ 3. Rc4 (3. Kd3 Rb8) 3... Rb8 4. Rc6 Kd5 5. Ra6 Rc8+ 6. Kb3 Rc6!) 3. Rd7 (3. b5 Rb8 4. Rh4 Kd6 5. Kb4 Kc7 $10) 3... Ke6! (3... Rb8? 4. Kc4 Ke6 5. Ra7 Kd6 6. b5 Rc8+ 7. Kb4 Rc7 8. b6) (3... Rc8+? 4. Kb3 Ke6 5. Rd4 Ke5 6. Rc4 Rb8 7. Rc6 Kd5 8. Ra6) *


