{ When the stronger side's king is in front of its own rook pawn on the a-file (or h-file), the position is a theoretical draw. The defending king only needs to reach c7 to achieve stalemate or deny the queening square — and here, the black king on e7 easily arrives at c7 in time. White's rook cannot generate progress because there is no room to build a bridge: the a-pawn's promotion square is shared with the corner, and the defending king always has access via b8 or c7. }
1. Rh2 { The draw is inevitable } 1... Kd7 2. Rh8 Kc7 3. Rb8 Rc1 (3... Rh1 4. Rb7+ Kc8 5. Rb2 Rc1) 4. Rb2 Rc3 *


