{ White's saving technique is 1.Rg8+!, giving check to force the king off the g-file and then adopting a "checking station" strategy — the rook oscillates from g8 to g5 and back, keeping Black's king busy and preventing the h-pawn from advancing without constant checks. The losing move 1.Rc3? lets Black advance h4 and reposition the rook to h7, after which the king marches in and the h-pawn decides. When defending against a rook pawn in this type of ending, long-range lateral checks are the key resource — the rook must never be passivized. }
1. Rc3? (1. Rg8+ Kf5 2. Rf8+ Kg4 3. Rg8+ Kh3 4. Rg5 h4 5. Rg8) 1... h4 2. Re3? (2. Rc6+ Kg5 3. Rc8 h3 4. Rh8 Kg4 5. Rg8+ Kf3 6. Rf8+ Kg2 7. Rg8+ Kh1 8. Rg6 h2 9. Rg8) 2... Rh7! 3. Re1 h3 4. Rh1 Kg5 5. Ke3 Kh4 6. Kf2 Rf7+ 7. Kg1 Ra7 8. Rh2 Ra1+ 9. Kf2 Kg4 *


