{ When the winning rook is in front of the a-pawn on the seventh rank and the defending king is nearby, the position is a theoretical draw regardless of any additional h- or g-pawn. The defending rook oscillates on the a-file (Ra1–Rb1–Rc1 cycling) preventing the white king from approaching, and if White's rook leaves the a-file to escort the king, Black captures the pawn or reaches b1, forcing a draw. An extra pawn on h5 or g5 is generally too slow to break the defense in this configuration — Black can ignore it. A pawn on f5 is the critical case (see next chapter): it is close enough to the black king to create an immediate tactical threat that cannot be ignored. } { [%cal Ra1a8,Gc5b6,Ba1b1,Bb1b8] }
 *


