{ This study is conventionally attributed to Peter Romanovsky (1950), though the same idea was published earlier by Orrin Frink (1925). It is a famous counterexample to the Vančura method: here the pawn is already on the sixth rank and White's king is much closer, so the standard Rf1+ Rf6 approach fails to a spectacular rook sacrifice (2.Ke5 Rf6 3.Rg8+!! Kf7 4.Rf8+). Black's only draw is the paradoxical 1...Rc1! — going to the c-file rather than checking — followed by 2...Ra1, reaching a position where White cannot improve because the defending rook targets the a-pawn from behind and the defending king pivots to f7. The study teaches that Vancura is not universal: precise calculation of the specific position is always required. }
1... Rc1! (1... Rf1+? 2. Ke5 Rf6 3. Rg8+!! Kf7 4. Rf8+) (1... Rb1? 2. Ra7+ Kf6 3. Ke4 Rb6 4. Rh7 Kg6 5. a7 Ra6 6. Rb7) 2. Rb8 (2. Ke5 Rc6) 2... Ra1 3. Rb6 (3. Rb7+ Kf6 4. a7 Ke6) 3... Ra5! (3... Kf7 4. Ke5 Ke7 5. Rb7+ Kd8 6. a7) 4. Ke4 Kf7! 5. Kd4 (5. Rh6 Kg7 (5... Ke7 6. a7 Kd7 7. Rh8)) 5... Ke7 6. Kc4 Kd7 7. Kb4 Ra1 *


