{ White draws with 1.Ra4+!, cutting off the black king along the 4th rank so the a-pawn cannot advance without the king's support, and after 1...Kf5 2.Rc4 the rook holds the drawing position. The losing 1.Rg6+? misplaces the rook and allows Black's king to approach via f4, after which the rook loses its cutting-off ability. The critical drawing resource missed later is 4.Rh4!! — retreating the rook to the fourth rank and then shuffling (Rh3–Rf3–Ra3) to neutralize the pawn — demonstrating that the defending rook must find counterplay along the rank rather than chasing the enemy king. }
1. Rg6+? (1. Ra4+ Kf5 2. Rc4 Ra2+ 3. Kh3 Rb2 4. Ra4) 1... Kf4 (1... Kf5 2. Rg3) 2. Ra6 (2. Rg3 Rg1+) (2. Rf6+ Ke4 3. Rc6 Ra2+ 4. Kg3 Rb2) 2... Ke4 3. Ra4+ Ke3? 4. Rg4? (4. Rh4!! Kd2 5. Rh3! Kc2 6. Rf3! a2 7. Rf2+ Kc3 8. Rf3+! Kc4 9. Ra3) 4... Ra2+! 5. Kh3 Rf2! 6. Ra4 a2 7. Ra3+ Kd4 8. Kg3 Rb2 9. Kf4 Kc4 $19 *

